Create the Policy Definition (this only stores the rule)
Assign the Policy (this is where it actually enforces and deploys)

Nothing happens until the policy is assigned



Phase 1: Create the Custom Policy Definition
This step only defines the logic.
No resources are touched yet.

Step 1.1 – Go to Policy Definitions

Azure Portal
Search Policy
Go to Definitions
Click + Create definition


Step 1.2 – Use the JSON editor (important)

On the Create policy definition page
Switch to the JSON tab
Paste the portal‑safe JSON

This step is only saving the policy logic.

Step 1.3 – Fill basic metadata
Still on the same screen:

Field  			What to enter
Definition location     Management Group or Subscription
Name			e.g. Deploy-VM-Diagnostics-LAW
Category		Monitoring (recommended)

Click Save
Result: Policy Definition exists and No enforcement yet

Phase 2: Assign the Custom Policy (This is where enforcement happens)
Now Azure will:

Create a managed identity
Grant permissions
Deploy diagnostic settings


Step 2.1 – Start Policy Assignment

Open the policy definition you just created
Click Assign

Step 2.2 – Basics tab

Setting  	   What to do
Scope    	   Subscription or Management 
Group              ExclusionsOptional
Policy enforcement Enabled

Best practice:
Assign at Management Group if possible or subscription level

Step 2.3 – Parameters tab (very important)
Here Azure asks for:
Log Analytics Workspace Resource ID
Paste the FULL resource ID, for example:
/subscriptions/<sub-id>/resourceGroups/<rg-name>/providers/Microsoft.OperationalInsights/workspaces/<workspace-name>

This tells Azure where diagnostic settings must point

Step 2.4 – Identity tab (MANDATORY)

Go to Identity
Enable: System‑assigned managed identity

Why this matters: DeployIfNotExists needs an identity to create diagnostic settings


Step 2.5 – Role definitions (what you just saw)
Because the policy creates resources, Azure must grant it permissions.
Select ONLY this role: Log Analytics Contributor

Why?

Allows creating diagnostic settings
Allows writing to Log Analytics
Least privilege

Do NOT select:

Contributor
Owner
Monitoring Contributor

Click Save

Azure now: Creates a managed identity and Assigns Log Analytics Contributor to it automatically


Step 2.6 – Complete assignment
Review → Create
Policy is now active

Phase 3: Remediation (Don’t skip)
By default:

New resources → compliant automatically
Existing resources → NOT fixed yet

You must remediate.

Step 3.1 – Start remediation

Go to Policy
Click Remediation
Select your policy assignment
Create remediation task

Azure now:

Scans existing resources
Deploys diagnostic settings where missing


What Happens Technically After This
For each resource (VM / NSG / Storage):

Policy evaluates compliance
If diagnostic settings are missing:

Uses managed identity
Creates Microsoft.Insights/diagnosticSettings
Points to Log Analytics workspace


Marks resource Compliant


Summary (Mental Model)

Policy Definition
   ↓ (no action yet)

Policy Assignment
   ↓
Managed Identity created
RBAC assigned
   ↓
Remediation
   ↓
Diagnostic settings deployed
